John Edward: language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding exam scores, which only reinforces with individual and group success in sports, art, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 students everywhere in Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further and higher education, the career they have chosen and their place as global citizens.
As an educational center that can design and implement customized school programs, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and desired as an elective subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, it will make him conceited.
If you speak to him in his language, it will strike him in the soul."
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely on English alone when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year's recent exam results, we can note that languages outperform all other subjects with the highest success rate in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a higher grade of "5+".
The data, collected from 74 SCIS schools, showed that 72 percent of students achieved a higher grade of "5+" in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also achieved "5".
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly acquire in the future.
Languages are now seen at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics) in independent school programs, as well as elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission noted that of the reasons employers cited for failing to fill jobs, 17 percent were due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly mandatory in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more jobs looking for languages, these skills are necessary in a globalized world.
No matter what career one chooses, if they learn a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future having such a lifelong skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically give the polyglot an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to speak, and French was the only language spoken by over ten percent, i.e. 15 percent of people.
Therefore, investing in language teaching is now important for today's children.
Having more languages, especially those of developing economies, will equip children with better chances of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will differ according to the languages it teaches.
Several schools will focus on more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages considered most important in the UK when looked at in the future by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
No matter what your child’s interests are, there will always be numerous languages to choose from in independent schools, with professors who are specialists in the field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future brings.
At present, it cannot be denied, in the global business environment, that languages will continue to be vital to the future of the country, so this must be replicated in schools.
In fact, modern languages really should be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence for Scotland's young people.
"Il faut bien le faire" (that must be done).
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
