Charles Chaisler, a sleep medicine professor at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham Women's Hospital, is designing the course he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a speech about the impact of insufficient sleep on learning.
“At the end of the lecture, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me this now, in the last year?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told the Telegraph.
The course, offered for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, and improve general well-being.
Paul Barrera, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of health services at the university said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students had a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive assignments.
In one section, there is an image of a dorm where students press on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how insufficient sleep affects athletic performance and the importance of routine when going to bed.
In another section, participants learn about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks and strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, then prompts participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know it won't change the behavior of students right away.
But we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know about the health effects when you choose to smoke a cigarette," added Professor Chaisler.
A culture of pride with "working all night" still exists, he said, and moreover modern technology and increasing pressure on students mean that lack of sleep is a growing problem.
Having enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student's "secret weapon" in combating stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, which makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond Saw, a 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chaisler design the course after taking one of his classes last year, in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to act for a course throughout the student city.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar program before joining the competitive institution.
