A study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common and soprano bats, as well as long-eared brown bats and daubenton bats at Inverow Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry mobile research using handheld detectors.
Expert analysis of the sounds of all the recordings will determine the frequency depending on the type of bats.
A habitat map will then be developed to create a detailed picture of their behavior in the area.
Rob Dewar, a conservation advisor at NBC, hopes the results will reveal which areas of life are most important for bats and how each of the species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forests for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and Britain has declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development that affect beds and habitat loss.
Winds and lights also pose a risk, as do sticky fly strips and some chemical treatments of building materials, as do domestic cat attacks.
Bats aren't actually blind.
However, because of their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo-location technique to find insects and obstacles in the flight path.
NTS, which oversees more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens, and 76,000 hectares of land in the state, takes bats very seriously.
There are ten trained experts, who regularly conduct research, bedside inspections, and sometimes rescues.
The organization even established Scotland's first and only bat reserve on the Trive property in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten species living in Scotland.
Property manager David Thomson says the property is ideal territory for them.
"Here at Trive we have a great area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, very old two and very good dwellings.
But there's a lot of unknown stuff about bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us learn more about what they need to thrive."
He emphasizes that it is important to check if there are bats before property renovations are carried out because the unconscious destruction of litters can destroy up to 400 females and cubs, and destroy an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, torture or disturb or destroy their beds.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer at the Bat Protection Trust encourages the public to help.
