New information on red tide: Concentrations decline in Pinellas, Manati and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Commission, conditions of uneven blooming of algae have been observed in the area of Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide, a consequence of the blooming of red algae extends for about 130 miles on the coast from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
Parts of the red tide can also be seen about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, yet the number is smaller compared to last week.
A red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
During the last week, the following concentrations have been observed: mean concentrations in or on the coast of Pinellas County, low to high concentrations on the coast of Hillsborough County, common to high concentrations in or on the coast of Sarasota County, common to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, common to high concentrations in or on the coast of Leere County, as well as low concentrations in Collier County.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to occur in Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No cases of respiratory irritation have been reported in Northwest Florida over the last week.
